President Samia Suluhu Hassan has donated foodstuffs including rice, cooking oil, sugar and goats to groups of orphans and children living in vulnerable conditions in Dodoma and Zanzibar. Muslims across the world are on Tuesday expected to celebrate Eid el-Fitr, which is a festival for breaking the fast and marks the end of the holy month of Ramadan. In Zanzibar, an aide at the State House of the United Republic of Tanzania, Mr Juma Said, presented the donations to the children on behalf of President Samia. “The President feels pleased to see that all children are happy, particularly during celebrations like this one,” the Regional Commissioner for Unguja South, Mr Rashid Hadid Rashid, thanked President Samia. Today is Eid-el-Fitri day in Tanzania marking the end of fasting month Ramadan in which adult Muslims in good health are required to fast from dawn to sunset. Eid el-Fitr celebrations are marked by eating special foods, going out, and visiting friends and relatives. Speaking after receiving the donations, a male student Abdi Abdalla and his female counterpart Fezuu Joseph, living at the SOS village, on behalf of their colleagues, thanked President Samia for the donation,” starting, “We love you and pray for you Mama, and keep on supporting us.”